# Architecture Notes

## After cycle 1
- Change: extracted module-level `const PROCESSING_FEE = 5` and used it in the return literal instead of a bare `5`.
- Rationale: Rule 2 (Reveals Intent) — spec calls this "processing fee (R3)"; naming the literal makes the domain concept explicit and prepares for upcoming quote tests that all add +5 fee. Mass rose 2 → 3 but clarity trumps APP.
- Naming established: `PROCESSING_FEE` (module-private constant) for the fixed R3 fee component of a quote premium.

## After cycle 2
- Change: renamed local `base` to `basePremium` inside `runScenario`'s step.map callback so it mirrors the module-level `BASE_PREMIUM` lookup table and reads explicitly in the premium formula.
- Rationale: Rule 2 (Reveals Intent) — `base` alone is ambiguous (base of what?); `basePremium` matches the domain term used in the spec ("100 base") and ties directly to the `BASE_PREMIUM` map it is summed from. Mass unchanged at 30. Did not extract a `quoteStep` helper yet — too early with only 2 tests; will reconsider once item-modifier tests (curse, high-enchantment) land.
- Naming established: `basePremium` (local) for the sum of `BASE_PREMIUM[item.type]` across items in one quote step.

## After cycle 3
- Change: extracted explaining variable `firstInsurance = basePremium * FIRST_INSURANCE_RATE` so the premium formula reads as a sum of three named domain components: `basePremium + firstInsurance + PROCESSING_FEE`.
- Rationale: Rule 2 (Reveals Intent) — the spec describes "first insurance" as a distinct premium component (10% of base), parallel to `PROCESSING_FEE`; the formula now mirrors that vocabulary directly. Mass +1 (one binding) but Rule 2 > APP per project rules. This sets up cleanly for upcoming additive components (curse surcharge, high-enchantment surcharge, loyalty discount) — each will become its own named line in the same shape.
- Naming established: `firstInsurance` (local) for the 10% first-insurance premium component on `basePremium`.

## After cycle 4
- No refactoring (justified): Green added one row (`staff: 80`) to the existing `BASE_PREMIUM` table — purely additive data, no structural change. All names still reveal intent (`BASE_PREMIUM`, `basePremium`, `firstInsurance`, `PROCESSING_FEE` match spec vocabulary), no duplication present, formula reads as three named domain components. Extracting a `quoteStep`/`computeBasePremium` helper is still premature: per cycle-2 plan, defer until item-modifier tests (curse, high-enchantment) land — the next todo (`potion`) is yet another base-premium row, not a modifier. Touching the `?? 0` fallback now would pre-empt the dedicated CLI-error tests for unknown items further down the list.

## After cycle 5
- No refactoring (justified): Green added one row (`potion: 40`) to `BASE_PREMIUM` — same purely-additive shape as cycle 4. No new structural opportunities emerged. Names still match spec vocabulary; no duplication; the three-component formula (basePremium + firstInsurance + PROCESSING_FEE) still reads as the spec describes. Inlining the `results` binding would save 1 mass unit but hurt Rule 2 (the named `results` mirrors the output key). Extracting `computeBasePremium(items)` is still premature — the natural trigger is the 3-rune block-discount test (cycle 8 in the todo list), where pure lookup-and-sum first breaks down; refactoring now would be guessing at the helper's shape before seeing how component blocks fit. The `?? 0` fallback continues to be reserved for the CLI unknown-item-type error test later.

## After cycle 6
- Change: extracted explaining variable `rawPremium = basePremium + firstInsurance + PROCESSING_FEE` so the line `const premium = Math.ceil(rawPremium)` reads as a discrete rounding step.
- Rationale: Rule 2 (Reveals Intent) — the rune test (32.5 → 33) made rounding-up a distinct domain step (spec R3: "rounded up to the nearest G"). Naming the unrounded total separates "compose the premium from its named components" from "round up to whole G"; both intents now stand out at a glance. Mass +1 (one binding) but Rule 2 > APP. Did not extract a `quoteStep`/`computeBasePremium` helper yet — per cycles 2/4/5, that's reserved for the 3-rune block-discount test where pure lookup-and-sum breaks down; the next test (2 runes, no block) is still pure summation.
- Naming established: `rawPremium` (local) for the unrounded sum of premium components, prior to round-up.
const PROCESSING_FEE = 5;
const FIRST_INSURANCE_RATE = 0.1;

const BASE_PREMIUM: Record<string, number> = {
  sword: 100,
  amulet: 60,
  staff: 80,
  potion: 40,
  rune: 25,
};

interface Item {
  type: string;
}

interface QuoteStep {
  op: "quote";
  items: Item[];
}

interface Scenario {
  customer: { yearsWithMHPCO: number };
  steps: QuoteStep[];
}

export function runScenario(input: unknown): unknown {
  const scenario = input as Scenario;
  const results = scenario.steps.map((step) => {
    const basePremium = step.items.reduce(
      (sum, item) => sum + (BASE_PREMIUM[item.type] ?? 0),
      0,
    );
    const firstInsurance = basePremium * FIRST_INSURANCE_RATE;
    const rawPremium = basePremium + firstInsurance + PROCESSING_FEE;
    const premium = Math.ceil(rawPremium);
    return { premium };
  });
  return { results };
}
import { describe, it, expect } from "vitest";
import { runScenario } from "./claim-office.js";

describe("MHPCO Claim Office", () => {
  // --- Base premiums for single main items (R1, R3 fee, first insurance) ---
  it("empty item list → premium 5 G (processing fee only)", () => {
    const result = runScenario({
      customer: { yearsWithMHPCO: 0 },
      steps: [{ op: "quote", items: [] }],
    });
    expect(result).toEqual({ results: [{ premium: 5 }] });
  });
  it("single plain sword for a newcomer first contract → premium 115 G (100 base + 10 first + 5 fee)", () => {
    const result = runScenario({
      customer: { yearsWithMHPCO: 0 },
      steps: [{ op: "quote", items: [{ type: "sword" }] }],
    });
    expect(result).toEqual({ results: [{ premium: 115 }] });
  });
  it("single plain amulet for a newcomer first contract → premium 71 G (60 base + 6 first + 5 fee)", () => {
    const result = runScenario({
      customer: { yearsWithMHPCO: 0 },
      steps: [{ op: "quote", items: [{ type: "amulet" }] }],
    });
    expect(result).toEqual({ results: [{ premium: 71 }] });
  });
  it("single plain staff for a newcomer first contract → premium 93 G (80 base + 8 first + 5 fee)", () => {
    const result = runScenario({
      customer: { yearsWithMHPCO: 0 },
      steps: [{ op: "quote", items: [{ type: "staff" }] }],
    });
    expect(result).toEqual({ results: [{ premium: 93 }] });
  });
  it("single plain potion for a newcomer first contract → premium 49 G (40 base + 4 first + 5 fee)", () => {
    const result = runScenario({
      customer: { yearsWithMHPCO: 0 },
      steps: [{ op: "quote", items: [{ type: "potion" }] }],
    });
    expect(result).toEqual({ results: [{ premium: 49 }] });
  });

  // --- Component pricing and block discount (R1, R2) ---
  it("single rune for a newcomer first contract → premium 33 G (25 base + 2.5 first + 5 fee = 32.5 → up to 33)", () => {
    const result = runScenario({
      customer: { yearsWithMHPCO: 0 },
      steps: [{ op: "quote", items: [{ type: "rune" }] }],
    });
    expect(result).toEqual({ results: [{ premium: 33 }] });
  });
  it("2 runes (no block) → base 50 G; premium 60 G for newcomer first contract (50 + 5 first + 5 fee)", () => {
    const result = runScenario({
      customer: { yearsWithMHPCO: 0 },
      steps: [{ op: "quote", items: [{ type: "rune" }, { type: "rune" }] }],
    });
    expect(result).toEqual({ results: [{ premium: 60 }] });
  });
  it.todo("3 runes (block applies) → base 60 G; premium 71 G for newcomer first contract (60 + 6 first + 5 fee)");
  it.todo("4 runes (no block) → base 100 G; premium 115 G for newcomer first contract (100 + 10 first + 5 fee)");
  it.todo("7 runes (no block) → base 175 G; premium 198 G for newcomer first contract (175 + 17.5 first + 5 fee = 197.5 → up to 198)");

  // --- "Alike" components — same type only ---
  it.todo("2 runes + 1 moonstone → base 75 G (no block: different types); premium 88 G newcomer first (75 + 7.5 first + 5 fee = 87.5 → 88)");
  it.todo("3 runes + 3 moonstones → base 120 G (two separate blocks); premium 137 G newcomer first (120 + 12 first + 5 fee)");

  // --- Item-specific modifiers ---
  it.todo("cursed steel sword enchantment 3, newcomer first → premium 165 G (100 + 50 curse + 10 first + 5 fee) [integration example]");
  it.todo("steel sword enchantment 5, newcomer first → premium 145 G (100 + 30 high-ench + 10 first + 5 fee) [threshold]");
  it.todo("steel sword enchantment 4, newcomer first → premium 115 G (no high-ench surcharge)");
  it.todo("cursed steel sword enchantment 5, newcomer first → premium 195 G (100 + 50 curse + 30 high-ench + 10 first + 5 fee)");

  // --- Multi-item modifier scope ---
  it.todo("cursed sword + plain amulet, newcomer first → premium 231 G (sum base 160 + 50 curse on sword + 16 first on 160 + 5 fee)");

  // --- Policy-wide modifiers ---
  it.todo("plain sword for customer with exactly 2 years, first contract → premium 95 G (100 − 20 loyalty + 10 first + 5 fee) [loyalty threshold]");
  it.todo("long-standing 2nd contract: customer 3y, second quote, cursed sword enchantment 7 → premium 160 G [integration example]");

  // --- Claims: cap, deductible, clauses ---
  it.todo("standard claim: steel sword enchantment 3, damage 500 → payout 400 G; remainingCap 1600 G (cap 2000 − 400)");
  it.todo("standard claim on a rune (no enchantment/material), damage 200 → payout 100 G; remainingCap 400 G (cap 500 − 100)");
  it.todo("high-enchantment clause: steel sword enchantment 9, damage 1000 → payout 400 G (500 − 100)");
  it.todo("dragon-material clause: dragon sword enchantment 5, damage 800 → payout 700 G (800 − 100)");
  it.todo("both clauses (50 % wins): dragon sword enchantment 9, damage 1000 → payout 400 G");
  it.todo("enchantment threshold exactly 8: dragon sword enchantment 8, damage 1000 → payout 400 G");
  it.todo("payout rounded down: dragon sword enchantment 9, damage 801 → payout 300 G (400.5 − 100 = 300.5 → down to 300)");

  // --- Deductible per damage event ---
  it.todo("dragon attack damages sword (500) and amulet (300) → payout 600 G (deductible applied once per damaged item); remainingCap 2600 G");

  // --- Multiple items of the same type ---
  it.todo("policy with two swords → insurance sum 2000, cap 4000; dragon attack damages both (two entries 500 each) → payout 800 G; remainingCap 3200 G");

  // --- Cap exhaustion ---
  it.todo("single sword (cap 2000), two successive 1500 G claims → first {payout 1400, remainingCap 600}, second {payout 600, remainingCap 0}");

  // --- Insurance sum independent of block discount ---
  it.todo("policy with sword + 3 runes → insurance sum 1750 (block does not change insurance sum), cap 3500; small claim verifies remainingCap");

  // --- Cap is based on unmodified insurance value (not on modified premium) ---
  it.todo("cursed sword policy → cap is 2000 G (based on unmodified insurance value 1000, not on the modified premium); verify via a 1500 G claim that yields payout 1400 and remainingCap 600");

  // --- Error cases (CLI exit codes) ---
  it.todo("CLI error: quote contains an unknown item type (e.g. broomstick) → non-zero exit, error on stderr, no results on stdout");
  it.todo("CLI error: claim references an item not part of the policy (amulet damage when only sword insured) → non-zero exit, error on stderr");
  it.todo("CLI error: damage entry with negative amount (−200) → non-zero exit, error on stderr");
  it.todo("CLI error: more damages of a type than items insured (two sword damages, one sword insured) → non-zero exit");
});
